# TODO: Construct autoencoder
class autoencoder(nn.Module):
    
    def __init__(self, hidden_dim= 400, bottleneck_dim=10, img_sz=40):
        super().__init__()
        flatten = nn.Flatten()
        encode1 = nn.Linear(img_sz**2, hidden_dim, bias=True)
        encode2 = nn.Linear(hidden_dim, bottleneck_dim, bias=True)
        decode1 = nn.Linear(bottleneck_dim, hidden_dim, bias=True)
        decode2 = nn.Linear(hidden_dim, img_sz**2, bias=True)
        unflatten = nn.Unflatten(1, (1,40,40))
        

        # define encoder and decoder in seperate methods
        self.encoder = nn.Sequential(
            flatten, # 1600
            encode1, # hidden dim
            nn.ReLU(),
            encode2, # bottleneck dim
            nn.ReLU()
            )
        
        self.decoder = nn.Sequential(
            decode1, # bottleneck dim
            nn.ReLU(),
            decode2, # hidden dim 
            )

    def forward(self, x):
        encoded = self.encoder(x)
        decoded = self.decoder(encoded)
        decoded = nn.functional.normalize(decoded, p=1)
        
        return nn.Unflatten(1, (1,40,40))(decoded)

This simple autoencoder is built from an encoder and a decoder with a single hidden layer each. The decoder performs exactly the revcerse operation

# set up training data & dataloader for QCD jets only
class ae_data( torch.utils.data.Dataset ):
    
    def __init__( self, imgs, labels, qcd=True, top=False ):
        self.labels = labels

        # depending on input QCD, top or both are returned
        if qcd and not top:
            self.imgs = imgs[ labels == 0 ]
        elif top and not qcd:
            self.imgs = imgs[ labels == 1 ]
        elif qcd and top:
            self.imgs = imgs
        self.imgs = torch.Tensor(self.imgs).float()


    def __len__(self):
        return self.imgs.shape[0]

    def __getitem__(self, idx):
        return self.imgs[idx]

# load QCD only
train_dataset = ae_data(z_train, y_train, qcd=True, top=False)
test_dataset = ae_data(z_test, y_test, qcd=True, top=False)
val_dataset = ae_data(z_val, y_val, qcd=True, top=False)

trn_dataloader = torch.utils.data.DataLoader(train_dataset, batch_size=64, shuffle=True )
tst_dataloader = torch.utils.data.DataLoader(test_dataset, batch_size=64, shuffle=False )
val_dataloader = torch.utils.data.DataLoader(val_dataset, batch_size=64, shuffle=False )
In[]:
def batch_loss(model, loss_fn, x):
    x = x.to(device)
    pred = model(x)
    loss = loss_fn(pred, x)
    return loss
In[]:
def train_epoch(model, dataloader, loss_fn, losses, batch_loss_fn):
    for x in dataloader:
        optimizer.zero_grad()
        
        loss = batch_loss_fn(model, loss_fn, x)
        loss.backward()
        optimizer.step()
        losses.append(loss.item())
    return losses
In[]:
def val_epoch(model, dataloader, loss_fn, losses, batch_loss_fn):
    losses_epoch = []
    with torch.no_grad():
        for x in dataloader:
            loss = batch_loss_fn(model, loss_fn, x)
            losses_epoch.append(loss.item())
    losses.append(np.mean(losses_epoch))
    return losses

AUC score: 0.8220878460542878

We experimented with the last layer of the MLP autoencoder: loss and reconstructions were generally much better when there was no nonlinearity (ReLU/ Sigmoid) in the last layer.

Inspired by the observation that the sum of pixel values is always 1 in the original images (L1 norm), we tested the effect of adding a L1 normalization layer. This improved the Loss by almost an order of magnitude, compared to no final L1 layer.

Varying the bottleneck dimension had visable effect on the level of detail in the reconstructed images and the AUC in the ROC curve. For optimal results, we chose the highest bottleneck dim. of 20.

With an area under curve (AUC) of > 0.8, the MLP based autoencoder already does a good job at differenciating between expected outcomes and anomalies.

# TODO: Repeat everything for CNN
class CNN_autoencoder(nn.Module):
    
    def __init__(self, in_ch=1, ch=4, bottleneck_dim=20, img_sz=40):
        super().__init__()
        self.conv1 = nn.Conv2d(in_ch, ch, kernel_size=5,  bias=True, stride=1, padding=2)
        self.conv2 = nn.Conv2d(ch, ch, kernel_size=5,  bias=True, stride=1, padding=2)
        self.maxpool = nn.MaxPool2d(kernel_size=2, stride=2, return_indices=True)
        self.relu = nn.ReLU()
        
        self.flatten = nn.Flatten()
        self.encode = nn.Linear((img_sz//2)**2 * ch, bottleneck_dim, bias=True)
        self.unflatten = nn.Unflatten(1, (ch,20,20))
        
        self.deconv1 = nn.ConvTranspose2d(ch, ch, kernel_size=5, bias=True, stride=1, padding=2)
        self.deconv2 = nn.ConvTranspose2d(ch, in_ch, kernel_size=5, bias=True, stride=1, padding=2)
        self.maxunpool = nn.MaxUnpool2d(kernel_size=2, stride=2)
        
        self.decode = nn.Linear(bottleneck_dim, (img_sz//2)**2 * ch, bias=True)

    # define forward pass
    def forward(self, x):
        # cnn encoder
        x = self.conv1(x)
        x = self.relu(x)
        x, i = self.maxpool(x)
        x = self.conv2(x)
        x = self.relu(x)
        
        # mlp bottleneck
        x = self.flatten(x)
        x = self.encode(x)
        x = self.relu(x)
        x = self.decode(x)
        x = self.relu(x)
        x = self.unflatten(x)
        
        # cnn decoder
        x = self.maxunpool(x,i)
        x = self.deconv1(x)
        x = self.relu(x)
        x = self.deconv2(x)
        return x

CNN_autoencoder(
  (conv1): Conv2d(1, 32, kernel_size=(5, 5), stride=(1, 1), padding=(2, 2))
  (conv2): Conv2d(32, 32, kernel_size=(5, 5), stride=(1, 1), padding=(2, 2))
  (maxpool): MaxPool2d(kernel_size=2, stride=2, padding=0, dilation=1, ceil_mode=False)
  (relu): ReLU()
  (flatten): Flatten(start_dim=1, end_dim=-1)
  (encode): Linear(in_features=12800, out_features=20, bias=True)
  (unflatten): Unflatten(dim=1, unflattened_size=(32, 20, 20))
  (deconv1): ConvTranspose2d(32, 32, kernel_size=(5, 5), stride=(1, 1), padding=(2, 2))
  (deconv2): ConvTranspose2d(32, 1, kernel_size=(5, 5), stride=(1, 1), padding=(2, 2))
  (maxunpool): MaxUnpool2d(kernel_size=(2, 2), stride=(2, 2), padding=(0, 0))
  (decode): Linear(in_features=20, out_features=12800, bias=True)
)

One can see that the cnn autoencoder always yields the very same output image. We suspect that there is a problem with information flow through the bottleneck, so that the network tries to produce the best average output irrespectrive of the input over that it does not have any information.
